I say in Latin, pluit, ningit, itur, statur; that is,
it Rains, it Snows, we go, we stand, &re.
Ar. 5. Theme Simple is either Universal or
Singular.
Ae. 6. A. Universal is that which is apt of its
own Nature to be predicated of many things, as
Mmn, Horse, Plans, bre-
A Universal is said to be predicated of many
things either actually Existing, or at least such as
may Exist. So Man was, a Uniuersal when Adam-
only was in being; because Man was not only apt
of its oum Nature to be said of Adam, but of all
Men that were to be Born. So alcho the Sun be
really but One, it may yet, that is, the Term Sum,
be call'd a Universal, beeause many Sumis may be
made of the same Nature with this of ours
8. Universal is said to be of its own Nature
apt to be predicated; lest any one shon'd think
Hlomonymou Words, or Words given to many-
Singulars of the same Species; as, When many
Men are call'd Peter, to be Univensals: For Ho-
monymous, as Homonympus, are predicated of ma-
ny as to their Namos only, not Definnions, or, as
to their puen Natures.
Ade.7. The Singular is that which of its ow
Nature, is ant to be predieared only of One-
