Of the Calegories in general-
ds 11I. Categury is a Series of Things gradually
T dispos d under the same chief Genuu-
A Cntigtary is so call'd from the Greel Word
itumple tins, that is, to Abcnse; for it was a Word
us'd in the Forum, and from thence brought into
the Schools, and signifies to say or affirm a Thing of
any Body hut the School- men say Pradicate Farther,
a Categary either is taken for the Affirmation it self,
or for the Series and Disposition of those things
which may be affirmed of others under the same
Senuis. Such a Series Boethiin calls a Predicament.
We hive chosen rather the Greet Word-
A. 3. The Categories are Ten, Substance, Nvan-
tity, Suality, Ralation, action, Passion, Whe-
Where,
Srits, and Habit.
As. 3.

Aee.- 3. Of which the one is of Sulstances, the
rest of Accidents. This Number is taken from
the diversity of Questions which may be made
concerning the first and individual Substances,
as appears trom the very Appellations of the Gnte-
gories.
dx- 4. In these Ten are contain'd all things
which can be pradicated of any Subject; others
directly, others indirectly.
d- 5. That which directly, requires these Five
Conditions.
I. It must be a Pinite Being.
hy this Condition God is exeluded out of the
Categories: For altho' God be a Substance, yet is
he not put in the Category of Substance; for those
things which are directly plac'd in this Category
not only subsist of themselves, bur are subject al-
so to Accidents, as we shall hereafter make ap-
pear, which to think of Giod were impious, Be-
sides, the Genus, properly so call'd, of those things
which are directly plac'd in the same Calegory
must be the same: hut neither Substance, nor
any thing else, can be the Gemus properly so call'd
of things Finite and Infinite: God therefore be-
ing Infnite cannot be directly contain'd under
the Gemus of Finite Substances. Tet is he qui-
vocally revol'd to this Category. For Substance
is the Genus aquivocal both of God and Finite
Substances.
